The author, a former chair of the Senate Judiciary Committee, expresses pride in the work done to strengthen the federal judiciary by appointing highly qualified judges who uphold the Constitution and the rule of law. They highlight the diversity of the nominees and the breaking of barriers in the past two years. They mention the recent confirmations of Cindy Chung as the first Asian American and Native Hawaiian Pacific Islander judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit and Judge Gina Mendez-Miro as the first openly LGBTQI+ judge on the U.S. District Court for the District of Puerto Rico. The author emphasizes the importance of making the judiciary more representative of the nation and appointing judges from historically underrepresented backgrounds. They also mention their focus on appointing judges with public defender experience and the high percentage of women and people of color among the confirmed judges. The author expresses gratitude to both parties for their cooperation in achieving these milestones.